{
  "answer": "**Only one work in the corpus explicitly discusses women as recluses (a form of ascetic enclosure):** Charles Dunoyer's *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL I* (Chapter 8). It describes \"sinful women (the Recluses)\" who are permanently enclosed in houses as a penitential practice, with doors walled up and communication limited to a small window for essentials.[^1]\n\nNo other works in the 37-work corpus explicitly discuss women functioning as ascetics or recluses. Related concepts appear (e.g., generic ascetics in Indic *smṛti* texts like *Āṅgirasa Smṛti* or hermits in *Kuñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana*), but these refer to men or use neutral/male-gendered terms without specifying women.[^2] Christian hagiographies like Cynewulf's *Juliana* feature female saints resisting pagan marriage but not as ascetics/recluses. Poetic mentions of nuns or holy women (e.g., in Iqbal or Ghalib) are metaphorical, not explicit discussions of ascetic/recluse figures.\n\n[^1]: Charles Dunoyer, *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL I*, [paragraph](/works/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-i-6da8ce/08-iii-liberte-compatible-avec-la-maniere-de-vivre-de/translation/#p-031e18).\n\n[^2]: E.g., *Āṅgirasa Smṛti* 1 (multiple paragraphs on ascetics); *Kuñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana* 1 (hermitages of male *asuras* and sages).",
